# Room Name - TryHackMe: MegaCorp AI Chatbot — Threat Assessment
Date: 04 May 2026
Difficulty: Easy
Category: AI Security / Threat Modelling

# Scenario
Map risks to MegaCorp's AI chatbot architecture using the OWASP LLM Top 10 framework. The challenge was a three-phase exercise involving selecting relevant LLM vulnerabilities, mapping them to specific components in the architecture, and justifying each mapping with a risk assessment.

# Tools Used
- TryHackMe Attack Box
- Browser

# What I Did

Phase 1 — Selection
- Reviewed the OWASP LLM Top 10 and selected the 5 most relevant vulnerabilities applicable to MegaCorp's AI chatbot architecture:
  - LLM01: Prompt Injection
  - LLM02: Sensitive Info Disclosure
  - LLM03: Supply Chain Vulnerabilities
  - LLM04: Data & Model Poisoning
  - LLM05: Improper Output Handling

Phase 2 — Assignment
- Mapped each selected vulnerability to the relevant component in the architecture diagram across three trust boundaries: External Access (Web Frontend, API Gateway), Internal Services (LLM Inference, Model Registry, Vector Database, Knowledge Base), and ML Operations (Training Pipeline).
  - LLM01 and LLM02 mapped to: LLM Inference Endpoint (nodes 1 and 2 in Internal Services)
  - LLM03 and LLM04 mapped to: Training Pipeline (nodes 3 and 4 in ML Operations)
  - LLM05 mapped to: Web Frontend (node 5 in External Access)

Phase 3 — Assessment
- Justified each mapping with a risk rationale and severity rating:
  - LLM01 Prompt Injection > LLM Inference: The inference engine processes prompts directly, making it the primary layer where injected instructions can hijack model behaviour or bypass system prompts. Severity: High
  - LLM02 Sensitive Info Disclosure > LLM Inference: The model can regurgitate PII or confidential data from its training corpus or active context window during inference responses. Severity: High
  - LLM03 Supply Chain Vulnerabilities > Training Pipeline: Malicious third-party datasets or compromised libraries introduced at training time can embed backdoors that persist into the deployed model. Severity: High
  - LLM04 Data & Model Poisoning > Training Pipeline: Poisoned training data causes the model to learn manipulated or backdoored behaviours that survive deployment and are difficult to detect post-production. Severity: High
  - LLM05 Improper Output Handling > Web Frontend: Raw LLM output rendered without sanitisation in the frontend can execute attacker-controlled content as XSS in the user's browser. Severity: High

